{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/21348.Aesop_s_Fables", "title": "Aesop's Fables", "titleComplete": "Aesop's Fables", "description": "The fables of Aesop have become one of the most enduring traditions of European culture, ever since they were first written down nearly two millennia ago. Aesop was reputedly a tongue-tied slave who miraculously received the power of speech; from his legendary storytelling came the collections of prose and verse fables scattered throughout Greek and Roman literature. First published in English by Caxton in 1484, the fables and their morals continue to charm modern readers: who does not know the story of the tortoise and the hare, or the boy who cried wolf?", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1389064715i/21348.jpg", "genres": ["Childrens", "Short Stories", "Mythology", "Philosophy", "Folklore", "Literature", "Fantasy", "Fairy Tales", "Fiction", "Classics"], "asin": "0192840509", "isbn": "0192840509", "isbn13": "9780192840509", "publisher": "Oxford University Press", "author": ["Laura Harris", "Aesop", "G.K. Chesterton", "V.S. Vernon Jones", "Edward Julius Detmold", "Laura   Gibbs"], "publishDate": 1049958000000, "ratingHistogram": [1100, 4675, 27653, 43961, 46869], "ratingsCount": 124258, "reviewsCount": 2616, "numPages": 352, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/19117.Fathers_and_Sons", "title": "Fathers and Sons", "titleComplete": "Fathers and Sons", "description": "Bazarov\u2014a gifted, impatient, and caustic young man\u2014has journeyed from school to the home of his friend Arkady Kirsanov. But soon Bazarov\u2019s outspoken rejection of authority and social conventions touches off quarrels, misunderstandings, and romantic entanglements that will utterly transform the Kirsanov household and reflect the changes taking place across all of nineteenth-century Russia. Fathers and Sons enraged the old and the young, reactionaries, romantics, and radicals alike when it was first published. At the same time, Turgenev won the acclaim of Flaubert, Maupassant, and Henry James for his craftsmanship as a writer and his psychological insight. Fathers and Sons is now considered one of the greatest novels of the nineteenth century.A timeless depiction of generational conflict during social upheaval, it vividly portrays the clash between the older Russian aristocracy and the youthful radicalism that foreshadowed the revolution to come\u2014and offers modern-day readers much to reflect upon as they look around at their own tumultuous, ever changing world. Introduction by Jane Costlow", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1390793535i/19117.jpg", "genres": ["Philosophy", "Russia", "Literary Fiction", "Literature", "Russian Literature", "Fiction", "19th Century", "Historical Fiction", "Classics", "Novels"], "asin": "0451529693", "isbn": "0451529693", "isbn13": "9780451529695", "publisher": "Signet", "author": ["George Reavy", "Ivan Turgenev", "Jane Costlow"], "publishDate": 1107244800000, "characters": ["Evgeny Bazarov", "Arkady Kirsanov", "Prokofyic", "Vasiliy Ivanovic Bazarov", "Katya Nikolayevic Lokten Kirsanov", "Arina Vlasyevna Bazarov", "Piyotr", "Nicolay Petrovi\u00e7 Kirsanov", "Fenicka Kirsanov", "Yevdoksiya Kushkina", "Anna Sergeeyevna Odintson", "Matyei Ilyic Kolyazin", "Porfiriy Dlatonyic", "Masha Kirsanov", "Sitnikov", "Mitya Kirsanov", "Agafokleya Kuzminishna Kirsanov"], "places": ["Russian Empire"], "ratingHistogram": [986, 3889, 18683, 34636, 28248], "ratingsCount": 86442, "reviewsCount": 3856, "numPages": 244, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Read Russia Prize", "awardedAt": 1451635200000, "category": "Classic Russian Literature for Joaqu\u00edn Fern\u00e1ndez Valdes", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/270807.Burned", "title": "Burned", "titleComplete": "Burned (Burned, #1)", "description": "I do know things really began to spin out of control after my first sex dream.It all started with a dream. Nothing exceptional, just a typical fantasy about a boy, the kind of dream that most teen girls experience. But Pattyn Von Stratten is not like most teen girls. Raised in a religious\u2014yet abusive\u2014family, a simple dream may not be exactly a sin, but it could be the first step toward hell and eternal damnation.This dream is a first step for Pattyn. But is it to hell or to a better life? For the first time Pattyn starts asking questions. Questions seemingly without answers\u2014about God, a woman's role, sex, love\u2014mostly love. What is it? Where is it? Will she ever experience it? Is she deserving of it?It's with a real boy that Pattyn gets into real trouble. After Pattyn's father catches her in a compromising position, events spiral out of control until Pattyn ends up suspended from school and sent to live with an aunt she doesn't know.Pattyn is supposed to find salvation and redemption during her exile to the wilds of rural Nevada. Yet what she finds instead is love and acceptance. And for the first time she feels worthy of both\u2014until she realizes her old demons will not let her go. Pattyn begins down a path that will lead her to a hell\u2014a hell that may not be the one she learned about in sacrament meetings, but it is hell all the same.In this riveting and masterful novel told in verse, Ellen Hopkins takes readers on an emotional roller-coaster ride. From the highs of true love to the lows of abuse, Pattyn's story will have readers engrossed until the very last word.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1388719598i/270807.jpg", "genres": ["Teen", "Abuse", "Religion", "Contemporary", "Young Adult", "Mental Health", "Fiction", "Realistic Fiction"