{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/30672.Darkness_at_Noon", "title": "Darkness at Noon", "titleComplete": "Darkness at Noon", "description": "Darkness at Noon is a fictional portrayal of the nightmare politics of our time. Its hero is an aging revolutionary, imprisoned and psychologically tortured by the Party to which he has dedicated his life. As the pressure to confess preposterous crimes increases, he relives a career that embodies the terrible ironies and human betrayals of a totalitarian movement masking itself as an instrument of deliverance. Almost unbearably vivid in its depiction of one man's solitary agony, it asks questions about ends and means that have relevance not only for the past but for the perilous present. It is \u2014- as the Times Literary Supplement has declared \u2014- \"A remarkable book, a grimly fascinating interpretation of the logic of the Russian Revolution, indeed of all revolutionary dictatorships, and at the same time a tense and subtly intellectualized drama.\"Darkness at Noon (from the German: Sonnenfinsternis) is a novel by the Hungarian-born British novelist Arthur Koestler, first published in 1940. His best-known work tells the tale of Rubashov, a Bolshevik 1917 revolutionary who is cast out, imprisoned and tried for treason by the Soviet government he'd helped create.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1290053535i/30672.jpg", "genres": ["20th Century", "Philosophy", "Russia", "Literature", "Dystopia", "Politics", "Fiction", "Historical Fiction", "Classics", "Novels"], "asin": "0553265954", "isbn": "0553265954", "isbn13": "9780553265958", "publisher": "Bantam Books", "author": ["Daphne Hardy", "Arthur Koestler"], "publishDate": 446976000000, "characters": ["Nicolas Salmanovitch Rubashov"], "ratingHistogram": [372, 1094, 5188, 11542, 11658], "ratingsCount": 29854, "reviewsCount": 2030, "numPages": 216, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/493456.Extras", "title": "Extras", "titleComplete": "Extras (Uglies, #4)", "description": "A few years after rebel Tally Youngblood takes down the Specials regime, a cultural renaissance sweeps the world. \u201cTech-heads\u201d flaunt their latest gadgets, \u201ckickers\u201d spread gossip and trends, and \u201csurge monkeys\u201d are hooked on extreme plastic surgery. Popularity rules, and everyone craves fame.Fifteen-year-old Aya Fuse is no exception. But Aya\u2019s face rank is so low, she\u2019s a total nobody. An extra. Her only chance at stardom is to kick a wild and unexpected story.Then she stumbles upon a big secret. Aya knows she is on the cusp of celebrity. But the information she is about to disclose will change both her fate\u2026and that of the brave new world", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1388187650i/493456.jpg", "genres": ["Adventure", "Post Apocalyptic", "Science Fiction", "Teen", "Fantasy", "Futuristic", "Young Adult", "Dystopia", "Fiction", "Romance"], "asin": "1416951172", "isbn": "1416951172", "isbn13": "9781416951179", "publisher": "Simon Pulse", "series": ["Uglies "], "author": ["Scott Westerfeld"], "publishDate": 1191308400000, "characters": ["Frizz Mizuno", "Andrew Simpson Smith", "Aya Fuse", "Eden Maru", "Hiro Fuse", "David Strorm", "Fausto", "Shay", "Tally Youngblood", "Ren Machino", "Udzir"], "places": ["Japan"], "ratingHistogram": [4376, 13790, 34950, 35110, 28855], "ratingsCount": 117081, "reviewsCount": 5809, "numPages": 417, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Ditmar Award", "awardedAt": 1199174400000, "category": "Best Novel", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "The Inky Awards", "awardedAt": 1199174400000, "category": "Silver Inky", "hasWon": null}]}
