{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/341879.Just_Kids", "title": "Just Kids", "titleComplete": "Just Kids", "description": "In Just Kids, Patti Smith's first book of prose, the legendary American artist offers a never-before-seen glimpse of her remarkable relationship with photographer Robert Mapplethorpe in the epochal days of New York City and the Chelsea Hotel in the late sixties and seventies. An honest and moving story of youth and friendship, Smith brings the same unique, lyrical quality to Just Kids as she has to the rest of her formidable body of work--from her influential 1975 album Horses to her visual art and poetry.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1259762407i/341879.jpg", "genres": ["Nonfiction", "Biography Memoir", "Memoir", "New York", "Audiobook", "Art", "Autobiography", "Poetry", "Music", "Biography"], "isbn": "006621131X", "isbn13": "9780066211312", "publisher": "Ecco", "author": ["Patti Smith"], "publishDate": 1263888000000, "characters": ["Robert Mapplethorpe", "Patti Smith"], "places": ["New York (State)", "New York City, New York"], "ratingHistogram": [6774, 10692, 35022, 80456, 130082], "ratingsCount": 263026, "reviewsCount": 19066, "numPages": 304, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "National Book Award", "awardedAt": 1262332800000, "category": "Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Stonewall Book Award", "awardedAt": 1293868800000, "category": "Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Lambda Literary Award", "awardedAt": 1262332800000, "category": "Bisexual Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Critics Circle Award", "awardedAt": 1262332800000, "category": "Autobiography", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "NAIBA Book of the Year", "awardedAt": 1262332800000, "category": "Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Goodreads Choice Award", "awardedAt": 1262332800000, "category": "Memoir and Autobiography", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6507691-the-manufactured-identity", "title": "The Manufactured Identity", "titleComplete": "The Manufactured Identity (Manufactured Identity, #1)", "description": "Months after his mysterious disappearance from a routine fishing trip, no one really expects over-the-hill Texas housewife Lory Latchley to find her missing husband--especially her husband. The Manufactured Identity is clinical psychologist Heath Sommer's ever-escalating immersion into the world of unlikely friends who each awaken to find their faithful companions missing without warning or reason. Desperate to find meaning in their pain, they are thrust by the auspices of fate into a common thread of mystery and human frailty. In the end, the fate of all may reside in the unstable hands of rookie pastor John Joe, but ultimately Lory and her newfound partners will uncover a truth so unnerving it makes even infidelity look palatable.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1388188833i/6507691.jpg", "genres": ["Psychological Thriller", "Suspense", "Crime", "Mystery Thriller", "Psychology", "Contemporary", "Fiction", "Mystery", "Thriller"], "asin": "1606965506", "isbn": "1606965506", "isbn13": "9781606965504", "publisher": "Tate Publishing & Enterprises", "series": ["Manufactured Identity"], "author": ["Heath Sommer"], "publishDate": 1245740400000, "places": ["The United States of America"], "ratingHistogram": [35, 60, 116, 84, 138], "ratingsCount": 433, "reviewsCount": 111, "numPages": 308, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17349.The_Demon_Haunted_World", "title": "The Demon-Haunted World: Science as a Candle in the Dark", "titleComplete": "The Demon-Haunted World: Science as a Candle in the Dark", "description": "How can we make intelligent decisions about our increasingly technology-driven lives if we don\u2019t understand the difference between the myths of pseudoscience and the testable hypotheses of science? Pulitzer Prize-winning author and distinguished astronomer Carl Sagan argues that scientific thinking is critical not only to the pursuit of truth but to the very well-being of our democratic institutions.Casting a wide net through history and culture, Sagan examines and authoritatively debunks such celebrated fallacies of the past as witchcraft, faith healing, demons, and UFOs. And yet, disturbingly, in today's so-called information age, pseudoscience is burgeoning with stories of alien abduction, channeling past lives, and communal hallucinations commanding growing attention and respect. As Sagan demonstrates with lucid eloquence, the siren song of unreason is not just a cultural wrong turn but a dangerous plunge into darkness that threatens our most basic freedoms.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1553691804i/17349.jpg", "genres": ["Skepticism", "Popular Science", "Nonfiction", "Philosophy", "Atheism", "Science", "Religion", "History", "Psychology", "Physics"], "asin": "0345409469", "isbn": "0345409469", "isbn13": "9780345409461", "publisher": "Random House Publishing Group", "author": ["Carl Sagan", "Ann Druyan"], "publishDate": 856857600000, "ratingHistogram": [1540, 2386, 8441, 21195, 38159], "ratingsCount": 71721, "reviewsCount": 3745, "numPages": 459, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Los Angeles Times Book Prize", "awardedAt": 820483200000, "category": "Science and Technology", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25614492-salt-to-the-sea", "title": "Salt to the Sea", "titleComplete": "Salt to the Sea", "description": "While the Titanic and Lusitania are both well-documented disasters, the single greatest tragedy in maritime history is the little-known January 30, 1945 sinking in the Baltic Sea by a Soviet submarine of the Wilhelm Gustloff, a German cruise liner that was supposed to ferry wartime personnel and refugees to safety from the advancing Red Army. The ship was overcrowded with more than 10,500 passengers \u2014 the intended capacity was approximately 1,800 \u2014 and more than 9,000 people, including 5,000 children, lost their lives. Sepetys (writer of 'Between Shades of Gray') crafts four fictionalized but historically accurate voices to convey the real-life tragedy. Joana, a Lithuanian with nursing experience; Florian, a Prussian soldier fleeing the Nazis with stolen treasure; and Emilia, a Polish girl close to the end of her pregnancy, converge on their escape journeys as Russian troops advance; each will eventually meet Albert, a Nazi peon with delusions of grandeur, assigned to the Gustloff decks.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1437084512i/25614492.jpg", "genres": ["War", "Teen", "Survival", "World War II", "Historical", "Young Adult", "Fiction", "Audiobook", "Historical Fiction", "Romance"], "asin": "0399160302", "publisher": "Philomel Books", "author": ["Ruta Sepetys"], "publishDate": 1454400000000, "characters": ["Alfred Frick", "Joana", "Florian Beck", "Emilia"], "places": ["Baltic Sea", "East Prussia"], "ratingHistogram": [1550, 3556, 19794, 71538, 102347], "ratingsCount": 198785, "reviewsCount": 25047, "numPages": 391, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "SCBWI Golden Kite Award", "awardedAt": 1483257600000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Audie Award", "awardedAt": 1483257600000, "category": "Young Adult", "hasWon": 