{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2666.The_Bonfire_of_the_Vanities", "title": "The Bonfire of the Vanities", "titleComplete": "The Bonfire of the Vanities", "description": "Alternate cover edition of ISBN 9780553381344.The Bonfire of the Vanities is a 1987 satirical novel by Tom Wolfe. The story is a drama about ambition, racism, social class, politics, and greed in 1980s New York City, and centers on three main characters: WASP bond trader Sherman McCoy, Jewish assistant district attorney Larry Kramer, and British expatriate journalist Peter Fallow.The novel was originally conceived as a serial in the style of Charles Dickens' writings: It ran in 27 installments in Rolling Stone starting in 1984. Wolfe heavily revised it before it was published in book form. The novel was a bestseller and a phenomenal success, even in comparison with Wolfe's other books. It has often been called the quintessential novel of the 1980s.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1542903489i/2666.jpg", "genres": ["Humor", "20th Century", "Literary Fiction", "Literature", "Contemporary", "New York", "Fiction", "American", "Classics", "Novels"], "publisher": "Dial Press Trade Paperback", "author": ["Tom Wolfe"], "publishDate": 1004428800000, "characters": ["Ferdinand Arguello", "John Campbell McCoy", "Peter Fallow", "St. John Thomas", "Jimmy Caughey", "Red Pitt", "Caroline Heftshank", "Mike Bellavita", "Greg Rosenwald", "Sherman McCoy", "Asher Herzfeld", "Brian Highridge", "Gil Archer", "Gloria Dawson", "Kate di Ducci", "Warren Bottomley", "Guliaggi", "Arthur Ruskin", "Annie Lamb", "Irv Stone", "Huck Thigg", "Lewis Sanderson", "Miss Lyons", "Alex Britt-Withers", "Bernard Levy", "Linwood Talley", "Eugene Lopwitz", "Nick Stopping", "Baron Hochswald"], "places": ["New York (State)", "New York City, New York"], "ratingHistogram": [1909, 4990, 17642, 30258, 24737], "ratingsCount": 79536, "reviewsCount": 3477, "numPages": 690