{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2767.A_People_s_History_of_the_United_States", "title": "A People's History of the United States", "titleComplete": "A People's History of the United States", "description": "In the book, Zinn presented a different side of history from the more traditional \"fundamental nationalist glorification of country\". Zinn portrays a side of American history that can largely be seen as the exploitation and manipulation of the majority by rigged systems that hugely favor a small aggregate of elite rulers from across the orthodox political parties.A People's History has been assigned as reading in many high schools and colleges across the United States. It has also resulted in a change in the focus of historical work, which now includes stories that previously were ignoredLibrary Journal calls Howard Zinn\u2019s book \u201ca brilliant and moving history of the American people from the point of view of those\u2026whose plight has been largely omitted from most histories.\u201d", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1494279423i/2767.jpg", "genres": ["Nonfiction", "The United States Of America", "Historical", "History", "Social Justice", "American History", "Politics", "Audiobook", "American", "Classics"], "asin": "B007CDYGTO", "isbn": "0060838655", "isbn13": "9780060838652", "publisher": "Harper Perennial", "author": ["Howard Zinn"], "publishDate": 788947200000, "places": ["The United States of America"], "ratingHistogram": [11885, 11865, 34182, 68565, 111246], "ratingsCount": 237743, "reviewsCount": 6955, "numPages": 729, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "National Book Award Finalist", "awardedAt": 347184000000, "category": "History (Paperback)", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15622.Native_Son", "title": "Native Son", "titleComplete": "Native Son", "description": "Right from the start, Bigger Thomas had been headed for jail. It could have been for assault or petty larceny; by chance, it was for murder and rape. Native Son tells the story of this young black man caught in a downward spiral after he kills a young white woman in a brief moment of panic.Set in Chicago in the 1930s, Wright's powerful novel is an unsparing reflection on the poverty and feelings of hopelessness experienced by people in inner cities across the country and of what it means to be black in America.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1627788308i/15622.jpg", "genres": ["Race", "Literature", "Banned Books", "School", "Fiction", "American", "African American", "Historical Fiction", "Classics", "Novels"], "publisher": "Harper Perennial Modern Classics", "author": ["Richard Wright"], "publishDate": 1122966000000, "characters": ["Mrs. Dalton", "Boris Max", "Buddy Thomas", "Vera Thomas", "Mary Dalton", "Henry Dalton", "Mrs. Thomas", "Jan Erlone", "Bigger Thomas"], "places": ["Chicago, Illinois", "Illinois"], "ratingHistogram": [2320, 4793, 17638, 36172, 36591], "ratingsCount": 97514, "reviewsCount": 4850, "numPages": 504, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "New York Drama Critics' Circle Award", "awardedAt": null, "category": "Best American Play", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7445.The_Glass_Castle", "title": "The Glass Castle", "titleComplete": "The Glass Castle", "description": "THE #1 NEW YORK TIMES BESTSELLERThe Glass Castle is a remarkable memoir of resilience and redemption, and a revelatory look into a family at once deeply dysfunctional and uniquely vibrant. When sober, Jeannette's brilliant and charismatic father captured his children's imagination, teaching them physics, geology, and how to embrace life fearlessly. But when he drank, he was dishonest and destructive. Her mother was a free spirit who abhorred the idea of domesticity and didn't want the responsibility of raising a family. The Walls children learned to take care of themselves. They fed, clothed, and protected one another, and eventually found their way to New York. Their parents followed them, choosing to be homeless even as their children prospered.The Glass Castle is truly astonishing--a memoir permeated by the intense love of a peculiar but loyal family.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1523542886i/7445.jpg", "genres": ["Nonfiction", "Biography Memoir", "Memoir", "School", "Contemporary", "Adult", "Audiobook", "Book Club", "Autobiography", "Biography"], "asin": "074324754X", "isbn": "074324754X", "isbn13": "9780743247542", "publisher": "Scribner", "author": ["Jeannette Walls"], "publishDate": 1137484800000, "characters": ["Maureen Walls", "Rex Walls", "Jeannette Walls", "Rose Mary Walls", "Lori Walls", "Brian Walls"], "places": ["New York City, New York", "West Virginia"], "ratingHistogram": [13595, 29602, 134255, 389181, 592354], "ratingsCount": 1158987, "reviewsCount": 60963, "numPages": 288, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "ALA Alex Award", "awardedAt": 1136102400000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Lincoln Award", "awardedAt": 1199174400000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}]}
