{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6759.Infinite_Jest", "title": "Infinite Jest", "titleComplete": "Infinite Jest", "description": "A gargantuan, mind-altering tragi-comedy about the Pursuit of Happiness in America. Set in an addicts' halfway house and a tennis academy, and featuring the most endearingly screwed-up family to come along in recent fiction, Infinite Jest explores essential questions about what entertainment is and why it has come to so dominate our lives; about how our desire for entertainment affects our need to connect with other people; and about what the pleasures we choose say about who we are. Equal parts philosophical quest and screwball comedy, Infinite Jest bends every rule of fiction without sacrificing for a moment its own entertainment value. It is an exuberant, uniquely American exploration of the passions that make us human\u2014and one of those rare books that renew the idea of what a novel can do.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1446876799i/6759.jpg", "genres": ["Humor", "Philosophy", "Literary Fiction", "Literature", "Contemporary", "Fiction", "American", "Unfinished", "Classics", "Novels"], "publisher": "Back Bay Books", "author": ["David Foster Wallace"], "publishDate": 1104566400000, "characters": ["Donald W. Gately", "Remy Marathe", "Pat Montesian", "Emil Minty", "Lyle", "Hal Incandenza", "Poor Tony Krause", "Gerhardt Schtitt", "Ann Kittenplan", "Harriet Bonk-Green", "Clenette Henderson", "Orin Incandenza", "Ted Schacht", "Geoffrey Day", "Mario Incandenza", "Randy Lenz", "Hugh Steeply", "Ortho Stice", "Bruce Green", "Dr. James Orin Incandenza", "Ken Erdedy", "Trevor Axford", "Jim Troelsch", "LaMont Chu", "Joelle Van Dyne", "Avril Incandenza", "Michael Pemulis", "Katherine Ann Gompert", "Dr. Charles Tavis", "Mildred L. Bonk", "Tiny Ewell"], "places": ["Boston, Massachusetts", "Ennet House", "Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)", "Tucson, Arizona",