{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16902.Walden", "title": "Walden", "titleComplete": "Walden", "description": "Originally published in 1854, Walden; or, Life in the Woods, is a vivid account of the time that Henry D. Thoreau lived alone in a secluded cabin at Walden Pond. It is one of the most influential and compelling books in American literature. This new paperback edition-introduced by noted American writer John Updike-celebrates the 150th anniversary of this classic work. Much of Walden's material is derived from Thoreau's journals and contains such engaging pieces as \"Reading\" and \"The Pond in the Winter\" Other famous sections involve Thoreau's visits with a Canadian woodcutter and with an Irish family, a trip to Concord, and a description of his bean field. This is the complete and authoritative text of Walden-as close to Thoreau's original intention as all available evidence allows. For the student and for the general reader, this is the ideal presentation of Thoreau's great document of social criticism and dissent.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1630470982i/16902.jpg", "genres": ["Environment", "Nonfiction", "Philosophy", "Memoir", "Literature", "Nature", "American", "Essays", "Classics", "Biography"], "publisher": "Princeton University Press", "author": ["Bill McKibben", "Henry David Thoreau"], "publishDate": 1082271600000, "characters": ["Henry David Thoreau"], "places": ["The United States of America", "Concord, Massachusetts"], "ratingHistogram": [8112, 16183, 42840, 59706, 58211], "ratingsCount": 185052, "reviewsCount": 7405, "numPages": 352, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/10959.Sophie_s_World", "title": "Sophie's World", "titleComplete": "Sophie's World", "description": "An alternative cover for this ISBN can be found hereOne day fourteen-year-old Sophie Amundsen comes home from school to find in her mailbox two notes, with one question on each: \"Who are you?\" and \"Where does the world come from?\" From that irresistible beginning, Sophie becomes obsessed with questions that take her far beyond what she knows of her Norwegian village. Through those letters, she enrolls in a kind of correspondence course, covering Socrates to Sartre, with a mysterious philosopher, while receiving letters addressed to another girl. Who is Hilde? And why does her mail keep turning up? To unravel this riddle, Sophie must use the philosophy she is learning\u2014but the truth turns out to be far more complicated than she could have imagined.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1343459906i/10959.jpg", "genres": ["Philosophy", "Scandinavian Literature", "Literature", "Fantasy", "Young Adult", "Contemporary", "Fiction", "Unfinished", "Classics", "Novels"], "asin": "1857993284", "isbn": "1857993284", "isbn13": "9781857993288", "publisher": "Phoenix", "author": ["Jostein Gaarder", "Paulette M\u00f8ller"], "publishDate": 788947200000, "characters": ["Karl Marx", "David Hume", "Aristotle (philosopher)", "Jorunn", "Charles Darwin", "Baruch Spinoza", "Cecilia Skotbu", "Ren\u00e9 Descartes", "Thomas Aquinas", "Socrates (philosopher)", "Sofie Amundsen", "Malaikat Ariel", "John Locke", "George Berkeley", "Jesus", "Plato", "St. Augustine", "Immanuel Kant", "Sigmund Freud"], "places": ["Norway"], "ratingHistogram": [6105, 15251, 51799, 89059, 90537], "ratingsCount": 252751, "reviewsCount": 14508, "numPages": 403, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Buxtehuder Bulle", "awardedAt": 820483200000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Premio Bancar