{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14891.A_Tree_Grows_in_Brooklyn", "title": "A Tree Grows in Brooklyn", "titleComplete": "A Tree Grows in Brooklyn", "description": "The beloved American classic about a young girl's coming-of-age at the turn of the century, Betty Smith's A Tree Grows in Brooklyn is a poignant and moving tale filled with compassion and cruelty, laughter and heartache, crowded with life and people and incident. The story of young, sensitive, and idealistic Francie Nolan and her bittersweet formative years in the slums of Williamsburg has enchanted and inspired millions of readers for more than sixty years. By turns overwhelming, sublime, heartbreaking, and uplifting, the daily experiences of the unforgettable Nolans are raw with honesty and tenderly threaded with family connectedness -- in a work of literary art that brilliantly captures a unique time and place as well as incredibly rich moments of universal experience.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1327883484i/14891.jpg", "genres": ["Literature", "Historical Fiction", "Historical", "Young Adult", "New York", "Fiction", "Book Club", "Coming Of Age", "Classics", "Novels"], "asin": "0061120073", "isbn": "0061120073", "isbn13": "9780061120077", "publisher": "HarperCollins Publishers", "author": ["Betty  Smith"], "publishDate": 1148972400000, "characters": ["Katie Nolan", "Neeley Nolan", "Mary Rommely", "Francie Nolan", "Thomas Rommely", "Sissy Rommely", "Johnny Nolan", "Eva \"Evy\" Rommely Flittman", "Sergeant McShane"], "places": ["New York (State)", "Brooklyn, New York City, New York", "New York City, New York", "The United States of America", "Williamsburg, Brooklyn, New York"], "ratingHistogram": [5043, 12513, 57846, 148129, 230075], "ratingsCount": 453606, "reviewsCount": 26028, "numPages": 496, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Audie Award", "awardedAt": 1009872000000, "category": "Classic", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/119322.The_Golden_Compass", "title": "The Golden Compass", "titleComplete": "The Golden Compass (His Dark Materials, #1)", "description": "Lyra is rushing to the cold, far North, where witch clans and armored bears rule. North, where the Gobblers take the children they steal--including her friend Roger. North, where her fearsome uncle Asriel is trying to build a bridge to a parallel world.Can one small girl make a difference in such great and terrible endeavors? This is Lyra: a savage, a schemer, a liar, and as fierce and true a champion as Roger or Asriel could want--but what Lyra doesn't know is that to help one of them will be to betray the other.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1505766203i/119322.jpg", "genres": ["Childrens", "Adventure", "Science Fiction", "Fantasy", "Young Adult", "Fiction", "Middle Grade", "Audiobook", "Steampunk", "Classics"], "asin": "B001NAR73E", "isbn": "0679879242", "isbn13": "9780679879244", "publisher": "Knopf", "series": ["His Dark Materials"], "author": ["Philip Pullman"], "publishDate": 829638000000, "characters": ["Lord Asriel", "Iofur Raknison", "Marisa Coulter", "Farder Coram", "John Faa", "Lee Scoresby", "Iorek Byrnison", "Billy Costa", "Lyra Belacqua", "Hester", "Serafina Pekkala", "Pantalaimon", "Roger Parslow"], "places": ["Oxford, Oxfordshire, England", "Svalbard, Spitsbergen"], "ratingHistogram": [47938, 82790, 274049, 476010, 609251], "ratingsCount": 1490038, "reviewsCount": 27172, "numPages": 399, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Guardian Children's Fiction Prize", "awardedAt": 820483200000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Audie Award", "awardedAt": 946713600000, "category": "Children's Titles", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Lincoln Award", "awardedAt": 1104566400000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Carnegie Medal", "awardedAt": 788947200000, "category": "", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4934.The_Brothers_Karamazov", "title": "The Brothers Karamazov", "titleComplete": "The Brothers Karamazov", "description": "The Brothers Karamazov is a murder mystery, a courtroom drama, and an exploration of erotic rivalry in a series of triangular love affairs involving the \u201cwicked and sentimental\u201d Fyodor Pavlovich Karamazov and his three sons\u2015the impulsive and sensual Dmitri; the coldly rational Ivan; and the healthy, red-cheeked young novice Alyosha. Through the gripping events of their story, Dostoevsky portrays the whole of Russian life, is social and spiritual striving, in what was both the golden age and a tragic turning point in Russian culture.This award-winning translation by Richard Pevear and Larissa Volokhonsky remains true to the verbalinventiveness of Dostoevsky\u2019s prose, preserving the multiple voices, the humor, and the surprising modernity of the original. It is an achievement worthy of Dostoevsky\u2019s last and greatest novel.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1427728126i/4934.jpg", "genres": ["Philosophy", "Russia", "Classic Literature", "Literature", "Religion", "Russian Literature", "Fiction", "19th Century", "Classics", "Novels"], "asin": "0374528373", "publisher": "Farrar, Straus and Giroux", "author": ["Richard Pevear", "\u0418\u0432\u0430 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430", "Borut Kra\u0161evec", "Fyodor Dostoevsky", "Larissa Volokhonsky"], "publishDate": 1024038000000, "characters": ["Katerina Ospovna Khokhlakov", "Fyodor Pavlovich Karamazov", "Mikhail Osipovich Rakitin", "Father Zosima, the Elder", "Dmitri Fyodorovich Karamazov", "Ivan Fyodorovich Karamazov", "Katerina Ivanovna Verkhovtseva", "Alexei Fyodorovich Karamazov", "Pavel Smerdyakov", "Nikolai Krassotkin", "Agrafena Alexandrovna Svetlova", "Ilyusha Snegiryov", "Liza Khokhlakov"], "places": ["Russia"], "ratingHistogram": [4015, 9268, 3